name: 1 Halliwick Road
description: A low energy refurbishment of an Edwardian house, with rear extension and loft conversion. Wood fibre insulation, MVHR, airtightness layer, triple glazing, timber structure and low embodied energy materials.

name: 1 Halsbury Close
description: Grade II Modernist House designed by German emigre architect Rudolf Frankel for his sister and family in 1938. The house remains relatively intact and retains the layout and original features which adhere to Modernist principles of the era.

name: 1.20 Oxo Tower Wharf
description: Unit 1.20 is one of 25 workshop and retail units in Oxo Tower Wharf and overlooks the courtyard towards the Bargehouse building from the first floor walkway. It is a multi-purpose space used as a workshop, showroom and teaching space.
address: Unit 1.20, The Courtyard, Oxo Tower Wharf, Bargehouse Street

name: 10 Tollgate Drive
description: Part of Austin Vernon & Parters designed estate completed 1966, 10 Tollgate Drive is range style house, refurbished in 2008 by Powell Tuck Associates,  owners are Angus and Sarah Shepherd, Angus is Director at Powell Tuck Associates.

name: 195 Mare Street
description: 195 Mare Street

name: 2 Bythorn Street
description: This ground floor flat was renovated in 2021//22  to create a two bedroom flat, courtyard lightwell, and open living space within the ground floor of a period end of terrace house (previously divided in the 1980’s).
address: 2 Bythorn Street, Ground Floor Flat, SW9 8AQ

name: 33 Buchanan Gardens
description: A residential family home. The architecture and design was created in collaboration with Studio 1 Architecture/Studio Fuse (practice has featured on Grand Designs) and Designer Decoresidence whose founder resides in the property.

name: 80 Mallard Place, Twickenham
description: This is a beautiful house in Eric Lyons' last SPAN development from 1982

name: 8a Belsize Court Garages
description: Originally a late 19C coachman's living quarters and stable, this mews house combines an award-winning architect's studio and spacious light-filled maisonette after a 2-phase carbon-reducing retrofit.

name: A Ruskinian Walk Through Shared Heritage
description: Ruskinian walk from RIBA award-winning Chiswick Business Park, Gunnersbury Triangle Nature Reserve through South Acton Estate, birthplace of artist Patrick Caulfield; Woodlands Park Ice House; to home of Wm Willett, of Daylight Saving Time
address: Building 3, Chiswick Business Park, 566 Chiswick High Road, W4 5YA

name: A bookshop for All
description: Newham Bookshop has been running for 45 years; it was founded in 1978. The bookshop plays an important role in this community, providing students, teachers, parents and the whole community with a rich variety of books.

name: A walk to work
description: Most journeys in cities like London take place because of need rather than choice. 'A walk to work' traces an epitome of such a compulsory journey - the daily commute and pinpoints the unexpected beauties in the backgrounds of the everyday.

name: Abbey Mills Pumping Station
description:
Abbey Mills pumping station 'A', built by engineer Joseph Bazalgette, Edmund Cooper and architect Charles Driver. Built between 1865 and 1868 it is described as the cathedral of sewage.
Follow this link to book: https://bit.ly/abbeymills

name: Air Raid Shelter, St Leonards Court
description: The Air Raid Shelter was first built in 1939 for the the residents of St Leonards Court. A dormitory annex with 48 beds was added in 1940.  Some of the original features, such as handmade lampshades, are remarkably well preserved.

name: All Saints Carshalton
description: 12C south aisle and former chancel. Blomfield nave, chancel, baptistry. Kempe glass, Bodley reredos and screen, spectacular Comper decorations, monuments and brasses, award-winning lighting scheme, fine modern benches.

name: Ancient Livery Companies in the City of London
description:
On this walk we shall discover some of the livery companies, learn about their ancient traditions and ceremonies, which are repeated every year. Also hear about  their important role in the City.
Free walks led by City of London Guides

name: BT Tower
description: An enduring, distinctive feature of the London skyline for the last 54 years, this is a rare opportunity for members of the public to visit the famous revolving floor, 158m above the capital. After the flight the guests can watch a history of the BT Tower film in our auditorium.

name: Baitul Amn Mosque
description: Guided Tour of the Mosque. Learn about the purpose of a mosque, listen to the call for prayer, observe worshippers offering prayers, ask any questions, get free souvenirs & literature. Refreshments will be served throughout the day
address: Baitul Amn Mosque, Royal Lane, Uxbridge, UB8 3QU

name: Bazalgette Mausoleum
description: Portland stone mausoleum built for Sir Joseph Bazalgette, composed of an obelisk above a square rusticated base, with steps leading down to the arched entrance of the vault.
address: St Mary's Church, 30 St Mary's Road, Wimbledon, SW19 7BP

name: Benjamin Franklin House
description: Grade I listed Georgian house, the only surviving home of Benjamin Franklin, retaining many original features including central staircase, lathing, 18th Century panelling, stoves, windows, fittings and beams.

name: Brentford Canal Toll House and Gauging Lock
description: Single-storey canal toll house (1911) where tolls were collected for passing through the lock. Grand Junction Canal connected the Thames at Brentford to the Industrial Midlands in 1794 at the height of the industrial revolution.
address: Grand Union Canal Walk, Brentford, TW8 8GA

name: Brentford Then and Now/Brentford through the Ages
description: The walk starts in the Medieval market place, proceeds  through 17C development and 18C housing then explores 19/20C industrial legacy and striking new 21C Thames-side regeneration schemes.

name: Brentham Garden Suburb
description: Britain's first co-partnership garden suburb, first houses built 1901. Parker and Unwin's plan introduced 1907, mainly Arts and Crafts style; fascinating social history.
address: The Brentham Club, 38 Meadvale Road, W5 1NP

name: British Cardiovascular Society
description: 9 Fitzroy Square is the home of the British Cardiovascular Society. In addition to original architectural features, visitors will be able to view the BCS collection of objects illustrating the history of cardiology. Last entry 3.30 pm.
address: British Cardiovascular Society, 9 Fitzroy Square, W1T 5HW

name: Brixton Windmill
description: A wonderful reminder of Brixton's rural past and inner London's last working mill. Built in 1816 by the Ashby family who produced flour until 1934.  Restored to working order 2011.

name: Brut House
description: The project was to build a south facing, upside-down, partially underground, passive, airtight, low-energy, infill-urban brutalist home, that would allow our family to stay within our local community.

name: Burton Mausoleum
description: Grade II* listed mausoleum in the form of an Arab tent with ripples in the stone imitating canvas. Interior is embellished with oriental lamps, devotional paintings and camel bells.
address: St Mary Magdalen's RC Church, 61 North Worple Way, Mortlake, SW14 8PR

name: Canons Park
description: Grade II listed historic park landscape containing several listed buildings, including an 18C 'temple' building, bothy and compound, and walled kitchen garden, converted in 1937 to an informally planted garden by Harrow Council.
address: Donnefield Avenue entrance, Canons Park, Edgware, HA8 6RH

name: Carnival of Invention
description:
A day-long takeover of Station Road celebrating local invention, community and creativity.

Bringing together the past, present and future of South Norwood with interactive arts & crafts, live performances, a feast and a go kart race.

name: Carshalton Water Tower and Historic Gardens
description: Early 18C Grade II listed building incorporating plunge bath with Delft tiles, orangery, saloon and pump chamber with part-restored water wheel. Hermitage and sham bridge in grounds.

name: Central Gurdwara (Khalsa Jatha) London
description: Central Gurdwara (Khalsa Jatha) London is the UK's oldest established Sikh Place of Worship. Originally founded in 1908 it has been at the current site since 1969 and have recently been refurbished into a modern Sikh place of worship.

name: Centre of the Cell and Neuron Pod, Queen Mary University of London
description: Neuron Pod is a striking 23-metre long and 10-metre high free-standing structure – designed as an extension to Centre of the Cell, an informal science learning centre at Queen Mary University of London’s Whitechapel campus.

name: Charlton House & Gardens
description: One of the U.K.'s only surviving Jacobean manor homes, set in Charlton Park, red brick with white stone dressings and classic Jacobean style. Each room has a unique fireplace coupled with beautiful strap work ceilings and original features.
address: Charlton House & Gardens, Charlton Road, SE7 8RE

name: Chartered Accountants' Hall
description: Late Victorian neo-Baroque building with modern-style 1970 extensions supporting 5 storeys of recently refurbished offices over the Great Hall.

name: Chiswick House and Gardens
description: Chiswick House and Gardens is one of the most glorious examples of 18th-century British architecture and landscaping with over 300 years of discovery, inspiration and delight.
address: Chiswick House and Gardens , Burlington Ln, W4 2RP

name: Church of St Lawrence, Little Stanmore
description: Unique Continental Baroque church rebuilt in 1715 by James Brydges, first Duke of Chandos. Painted walls and ceiling with trompe-l'oeil effect. Wood carvings by Grinling Gibbons and the organ on which Handel played.

name: City Hall
description: The sustainable new headquarters of the Mayor of London and London Assembly located in the Royal Docks, Newham.  The docks are re-emerging as a commercial and cultural hub, and an exciting new waterfront.

name: City Information Centre
description: London's main tourist information centre is clad in a specially manufactured system of 220 pre-finished stainless steel panels. The subtly reflective surface provides a striking counterpoint to St Paul's.

name: City Mill Pool Street
address: City Mill Pool Street, Pool Street, E20 2AF

name: College of Optometrists
description: HQ of professional and examining body for UK optometrists occupying two terraced houses, No. 41 (Flitcroft c1730 with later additions) and No. 42 (rebuilt by Tarmac plc, c1989) including Council chamber, print room, library and museum.

name: Cressingham Gardens
description: Low-rise high density estate located next to Brockwell Park. Innovative design with pioneering architectural elements & echoing natural topography. Under threat of demolition by Lambeth council. Tours provided of estate and rotunda.
address: Cressingham Gardens Rotunda, Tulse Hill , SW2 2QG

name: Croydon Minster
description: Medieval style church rebuilt by Sir George Gilbert Scott after 1867 fire. Tower & south porch are 15C. Large nave with open timber-work roof leads to chancel dominated by superb stained glass window & rich alabaster reredos.

name: Deptford's Black History before and after Windrush
description: A walk between two sites commemorating tragic events in South London's post Windrush Black History. Using local landmarks, this tour highlights the contrasting experiences of Deptford's pre and post Windrush populations.

name: Discovering Colindale - How Early Aviation Forged Colindale’s Development
description: Colindale played a pivotal role in early aviation in England with the establishment of the London Aerodrome. Later, the area was developed with manufacturing, scientific, and cultural repositories and became home to emerging suburbs.
address: Bang Bang Oriental Food Hall, 399 Edgware Rd, NW9 0FH

name: Dorich House Museum
description: The former studio home of the sculptor Dora Gordine and her husband the Hon. Richard Hare, a scholar of Russian art and literature. 1930s house over four floors including a flat roof terrace and views of Richmond Park.
address: Dorich House Museum, 67 Kingston Vale, SW15 3RN

name: Douglas Fir House
description: A low-energy, prefabricated Canadian Douglas fir rear extension to the garden flat of a converted Edwardian terraced house.

name: Ealing Centre and North
description: Walk led by Ealing Civic Society members, Jenny Gadsby and Josette Bishop. The walk will cover Ealing north of Uxbridge Road. Circumstances permitting, it will include a tea stop in the garden of one of the walk leaders.
address: Haven Green opposite Ealing Broadway Station, The Broadway, Ealing

name: Eames Fine Art
description: A great example of the rich evolution of London’s buildings; from noxious leather treatment warehouse complete with sloping floors, winch poles and loading platforms to a stylish hidden Art Collector’s Studio in the space of 150 years.

name: East House: The story of a self-built home in London
description: This house was built by its owners (2018-2022), which creates an acute sense of ownership and connection to the neighbourhood. It shows how small and redundant sites could be used to provide high quality and sustainable places to dwell.

name: Eastcote Walking Tour
description: Discover the fascinating history of Eastcote and its surroundings, focused on how the landscape has changed, from the exclusively agricultural area to the today's modern suburb, revealing some of the oldest local buildings and their stories
address: Eastcote Station, Field End Road, Pinner, HA5 1QZ

name: Fitzrovia Chapel
description: Loughborough Pearson's red brick building is unimposing from the outside, but inside is a riot of Gothic Revival design. Golden mosaics reveal the character of the Grade II* listed chapel, built as part of the Middlesex Hospital.

name: Founders' Hall
description: Begun in 1985, our fifth Hall is constructed of traditional materials in a manner which is in keeping with this historic part of the City.

name: Freemasons' Hall
description: The current building, the third on the site, was built between 1927-1933 in the Art Deco style, as a memorial to the 3,225 Freemasons who died in World War I. It is a Grade II* listed building, both internally and externally.
address: Freemasons' Hall, 60 Great Queen Street, WC2B 5AZ

name: From Forest to Morris: A walk around Walthamstow
description: A walk around historic Walthamstow showing how this unique area grew from a village into a thriving suburb, its social history and the variety of buildings that can be found where Epping Forest meets William Morris.
address: Outside Costa Coffee at Walthamstow Central Station 5 Station Approac

name: Fulham Road Picturehouse
description: Fulham Road Picturehouse takes us back to the glory days of 1930s period glamour in this stunning listed building. Earle Architects (who did a fantastic job with Bromley Picturehouse) have helped us revive Fulham Road to its former vintage
address: Fulham Road Picturehouse, 142 Fulham Road, SW10 9QR

name: Garden Barge Square at Tower Bridge Moorings
description: Floating gardens on the Tideway below Tower Bridge, home to a residential community of more than a hundred barge dwellers. Open House on Sunday 10th October from 14.00 - 18.00.
address: Access through Reeds Wharf, 33 Mill Street, SE1 2AX

name: Garrick's Temple to Shakespeare, Hampton
description: Grade I listed Georgian garden building. Tribute to Shakespeare built in the Ionic style by actor David Garrick. Arcadian Thames-side setting in restored 18C gardens thought to be by Capability Brown.
address: Garrick's Lawn, Hampton Court Road, , Hampton, TW12 2EN

name: Gateway Central and Gateway West building tour
description: Tours of two low energy workplaces in the heart of White City. Gateway Central - decorous, light, and well crafted - is L’Oréal's newest home. Linked by a public garden, Gateway West’s compact form and gravitas offers a deliberate contrast.

name: Gaunson Creative Open Studios part of Markfield Road Festival
description: Gaunson Creative Studios in South Tottenham, home to over 70 artist studios, will be opening its doors for the first time since 2019. Visitors will be able to meet and buy from over 50 artists across the weekend.
address: Gaunson Creative Studios, Gunson House, Markfield Road, N15 4QQ

name: Good Shepherd Studios
description: The doors to the building (including the artists' studios) will be opened to the public. Not only will visitors get the opportunity to see "behind the scenes" but they will have the opportunity to join workshops run by the artists/makers.

name: Greenwich Yacht Club
description: Contemporary timber and aluminium building using existing pier, offering unique views of the river, the O2 and the Thames Barrier.

name: Grove Gardens Chapel
description: A small, charming Gothic Revival cemetery chapel made from Kentish ragstone, with plate tracery and a mosaic alterpiece. It was deconsecrated and then restored for community use. Thomas Hardy was apprenticed to the architect.
address: Richmond Cemetery, Grove Gardens, Lower Grove Road, TW10 6HP

name: Guildhall
description: The City's seat of municipal government since 12C. Grade I listed, rare example of medieval civic architecture.

name: Guildhall Art Gallery
description:
UPDATED: Open daily 10.30am-4pm. 
Guided tours 12.15pm & 1.15pm on Tuesdays, Thursdays, Fridays, Saturdays & Sundays, see below.
Home of the City of London's art collection, & remains of London's Roman Amphitheatre

name: Hackbridge Passivhaus Plus Primary School
description: Guided tours of the UK's first Passivhaus Plus school, led by the architects. This is an opportunity to visit a leading zero carbon education space - a haven of ecology complemented by a palette of natural, low-carbon materials.
address: Hackbridge Primary School, London Road, CR4 4HS

name: Hammersmith Quaker Meeting House
description: This new Quaker Meeting House is designed to be highly sustainable. It embodies the Quaker values of simplicity and equality, promoting a sense of calm.
address: 30-32 Bradmore Park Rd, London W6 0DT, W6 0DT

name: Hampstead Friends Meeting House
description:
Listed Arts and Crafts freestyle building with plain interior and many charming original features, sympathetically modernised in 1991. Entrance via listed gateway.
NOTE Please wear facemasks.

name: Hawksmoor: The Devil’s Architect?
description: Join your tour guide for a tour of Hawksmoor’s  finest church, Christ Church, Spitalfields, where we’ll unlock the history of this fascinating area and building, as well as learning a new skill; how to ‘read’ a church. Covering the controversial myth about Hawksmoor and the occult, the tour will explain the social context of the construction of this church and its architectural importance.
address: At entry gates to platform 10 Liverpool St. mainline station.

name: Heath Robinson Museum
description: This NLHF supported, accredited, purpose-built museum in Pinner Memorial Park displays a collection of Heath Robinson’s work. It includes permanent & temporary exhibition galleries, activity space & shop. It was designed by ZMMA.
address: Pinner Memorial Park, 50 West End Lane, Pinner, HA5 1AE

name: Historic & Modern Buildings in the City
description:
On this walk we will see many historic & modern buildings. see different architecture styles having regard to the environment and sustainability, and hear about famous architects, past and present.

Free walks led by City of London Guides

name: Hogarth's House
description: Early 18C red brick home of artist William Hogarth extended significantly c1749-1764. A 2020 extension adds a curved glass wall in the shape of Hogarth's Line of Beauty. Delightful walled garden containing famous ancient mulberry tree.
address: Hogarth Lane, Great West Road, W4 2QN

name: Holy Trinity Church Sloane Square
description: A sumptuous feast of Victorian stained glass & bold sacred sculpture in what Sir John Betjeman called the 'cathedral of the Arts and Crafts movement.' Work by William Morris, Edward Burne-Jones, William Blake- Richmond & Christopher Whall.
address: 146 Sloane Street (just off Sloane Square), SW1X 9BZ

name: Home of Jermaine Gallacher
description: Jermaine Gallacher is an interior designer, product designer and design dealer renowned for his offbeat and distinctive style. His home within a nineteenth century Peabody block, houses his extensive personal collection.
address: Flat 66 Douglas Buildings, Marshalsea Road, SE1 1EH

name: How People Shape Space: Mural Painting
description: Join us  at the Lea Bridge Library,  as we collaborate with the public to create a wooden tiled mosaic, exploring how each individual views and experiences space.

name: International Maritime Organization
description: The International Maritime Organization is a specialized agency of the UN, responsible for the safety and security of shipping and the prevention of marine pollution by ships. It is the only UN organization with headquarters in London.

name: Jackson Lane Arts Centre
description: Jacksons Lane’s year-round programme of contemporary performance, arts participation and cultural education exists to empower, and ignite creativity within, diverse communities & work tirelessly to overcome traditional barriers through art.

name: Keats House
description: Keats House is the beautiful Regency villa, where Romantic poet John Keats found inspiration, friendship and love. Today, it is a museum provided by the City of London Corporation for the benefit of London and the nation.

name: Kempton Steam Museum
description: 1920s water pumping station comprising of several architectural styles. Interior retains original steam pumping machinery and historic electrical equipment.
address: Kempton Park Pumping Station, Snakey Lane, TW13 6XH

name: Kenwood
description: A striking Neoclassical villa in tranquil gardens on Hampstead Heath, Kenwood boasts breath-taking interiors by Robert Adam and a world-class art collection. For guaranteed entry, book your free ticket via the English Heritage website.

name: Kilmorey Mausoleum
description: Egyptian-style, pink and grey mausoleum created for the second Earl of Kilmorey. The form relates to the shrines at the heart of Egyptian Temples.
address: 275 St Margaret's Road (opposite Ailsa Tavern), TW1 1NJ

name: King George V Pumping Station
description: Designed to pump water from the River Lee into the King George V reservoir, the building houses three old disused gas Humphrey pumps, and two electric pumps currently in service.

name: Kingston Historic walk
description:
We are running our usual guided walking tours around historic Kingston this year with reduced numbers.

Our guided tours are informative, interesting and fun. For more information about us visit: https://www.kingstontourguides.org.uk/
address: Market house, Kingston upon Thames, KT1 1JX

name: Kingston Liberal Synagogue
description: An interesting conversion from a Victorian School to a Synagogue and Community Centre in the 1970s.
address: Rushett Road, Long Ditton, Kingston, KT7 0UX

name: Kingswood House
description: Grade II listed building. Substantial villa built in form of stone-faced baronial castle for the inventor of Bovril. An internal refurbishment is planned to convert it into a cultural and community space.

name: Leamouth and Silvertown walking tour
description: A tour exploring transformative new developments that are – as one advert puts it – ‘built on London’s history’. It will look at how sites such as Goodluck Hope, London City Island and Royal Wharf use and are shaped by their Docklands past

name: Lexi Cinema
description: A contemporary extension to the Lexi Cinema, providing a 2nd screen. The building is a composition of brick and stainless steel; a nod to the parapets of surrounding terraces and reflecting the ever-changing sky above.

name: Limehouse Town Hall
description: Limehouse Town Hall is a building and resource for artists and cultural producers, audiences and communities from Tower Hamlets and beyond to share ideas, celebrate, organise, and imagine a better here and now.
address: Limehouse Town Hall, 646 Commercial Road, E14 7HA

name: Lincoln's Inn
description: Lincoln’s Inn has been an association of barristers for over 600 years. An 11-acre site combining gardens with mediaeval, Victorian, Georgian, and modern buildings, including banqueting halls, a law library, a chapel, and teaching space.
address: The Honourable Society of Lincoln's Inn, WC2A 3QB

name: Little Holland House
description: Grade II listed building inspired by the ideals of John Ruskin and William Morris and contains Dickinson's paintings, hand-made furniture, furnishings, metalwork and friezes, in Arts & Crafts style. Reopening after a refurbishment project.

name: Little Mouse Cheese Shop
description: Visit Little Mouse, an Edwardian shop in South Norwood with original wooden frontage and fascia that is now an artisan cheesemonger.

name: London Buddhist Centre
description: If you've never been to the centre, come and find out how this derelict Victorian fire station became a hub of Buddhism in the West; and if you already come to the centre, delve deeper into its architectural secrets!

name: London Open Form Pavilion of Air
description: A floating roof of sound, GPS-triggered & accessed by headphones & Echoes app to playfully reframe public space as an essential community engagement. One of 15 in an international series drawing on Oskar & Zofia Hansen’s Open Form concept.

name: London Scottish House (London Scottish Regimental Headquarters)
description: A Grade 2 listed former Territorial Army Drill Hall  featuring restored elements of the original 1882 design. It has a triple height central hall with the restored wrought iron balconies and roofing.  Notable Neo-Georgian design brickwork.
address: London Scottish House, 95 Horseferry Road, Westminster, SW1P 2DX

name: London's Roman Amphitheatre
description:
UPDATED: Open daily 10.30am-4pm Closed Mon 19 September.
Combined guided tours of Amphitheatre and Guildhall Art Gallery at 12.15pm & 1.15pm on Tuesdays, Thursdays, Fridays, Saturdays & Sundays.
The capital’s only known Roman Amphitheatre
address: London’s Roman Amphitheatre at Guildhall Art Gallery, Guildhall Yard

name: Love Lane Green
description:
Visitors can drop in on the 10th September to view the garden.  Volunteers will be onsite to answer any questions about the community garden.
The 11th September there will be two guided talks, beginning at 11am and 3pm. No need to book.
address: Love Lane Green, Love Lane, Greater London, SE25 4NG

name: Markfield Beam Engine and House
description: A masterpiece of Victorian engineering, Markfield Beam Engine provided a vital public health facility from 1855-1964.
address: Markfield Park, Markfield Road, South Tottenham, N15 4RB

name: Maxwell House, Brackenbury Village
description: Maxwell House is a unique architecturally designed open-plan 4 storey home. Its design and tapestries are inspired by its rich history as a textile shop, & the Roberts family of drapers who lived there for 40yrs from the late 19th Century.

name: Moravian Close
description: A former stable yard of Sir Thomas More's Chelsea estate, now an 18C Chapel, other buildings, and burial ground. Parts of the enclosing walls are Tudor in origin. Ernest and Mary Gillick enhanced the grounds in the 20C.

name: Mother X Artists and Makers Open Studios
description: Mother X is a diverse group of artists, makers & creators that have inhabited a former Victorian chocolate factory in Hackney Wick for 15+ years. Come visit this unique building & see it's people & their work during the Open House Festival.
address: Floor D, Unit 9 Queen's Yard, Hackney Wick, E9 5EN

name: Museum of Brands
description: Join our historic talk on the history of the building. This site was originally the site for the Bayswater Jewish School, before becoming the London Lighthouse. Then in 2015, the Museum of Brands moved in.

name: Muswell Hill - Low Carbon House
description: An adventure in retrofit possibilities: starting with a wreck & a passionate client, we explored, researched and innovated to reduce the energy consumption by 90-95% using the lowest carbon solutions we could find.

name: National Liberal Club
description: An impressive Victorian neo-Classical building overlooking the Embankment of the river Thames. It is the second-largest clubhouse ever built, the first London building to incorporate a lift and to be entirely lit by electric lighting.

name: National Portrait Gallery Architecture Highlights Tours
description: Discover the architecture of the National Portrait Gallery, designed in 1896 by Ewan Christian and now transformed by Jamie Fobert Architects. Please meet at the Ross Street Entrance. Drop-in 16 & 17 September at specific times listed below.  But please note that spaces are extremely limited and tour places will be allocated on a first come, first served basis. Please arrive early to avoid disappointment.
address: National Portrait Gallery, St Martin's Place, WC2H 0HE

name: New West End Synagogue
description: The New West End Synagogue is among the most beautiful, historic buildings of Jewish interest in England and is a Grade 1 Listed Building. The texts that adorn the walls concentrate on the ideas of Divine knowledge and worship.

name: Norman Fisher Observatory
description:
The Norman Fisher Observatory is owned and run by Croydon Astronomical Society. 
Open for the public to visit on clear Saturday evenings from September through to April, we will welcome visitors on Sunday 10th September between 1pm & 4pm.
address: Waterhouse Lane, Off Hayes Lane, Kenley, CR8 5EP

name: Nunhead Cemetery
description: Magnificent Victorian cemetery with Gothic chapel & restored & ruined lodge. One of London's wildest cemeteries. Part restored with the help of a lottery grant. 52 acres of woodland, with bats, owls, foxes & squirrels. Grade II*  landscape.

name: Old Royal Naval College
description: Sir Christopher Wren's riverside masterpiece in Greenwich, built as the Royal Hospital for Seamen and begun in 1696.
address: Old Royal Naval College, Greenwich, SE10 9NN

name: Phoenix Cinema
description: One of the oldest cinemas in the country with a barrel-vaulted ceiling and Art Deco wall reliefs by Mollo and Egan. Grade II listed.

name: Phoenix Gardens Community Building
description: The first purpose-built new-build community centre to be built in the heart of Soho for generations, located within the renowned Phoenix Gardens. Winner: RIBA London Award. Designed by RIBA London Architect of the Year Winner.

name: Pitzhanger Manor & Gallery
description: Designed by Sir John Soane as a family home and country residence. Following a three-year conservation project,  Pitzhanger has been returned to Soane’s innovative original design and re-opened to the public in March 2019.

name: Public art trail: Portraits of the South
description:
Public art trail: Portraits of the South by Abi Partington-Moran 

This innovative artist-created trail in Sutton Town Centre is the first of four Sutton STEAMS Ahead photographic commissions to be unveiled this Autumn/Winter.

name: Pullman Court
description: Grade II* listed buildings, modern movement style with balcony walkways and period internal features.

name: Queen Mary  University of London, Mile End Campus
description: Explore the hidden corners of Queen Mary University's Mile End campus. Guided tour includes the former People’s Palace (1887), Mile End Hospital (1858), and the Sephardic Jewish cemetery (1733), the UK’s second oldest Jewish cemetery.
address: Queens' Building, Mile End Road, E1 4NS

name: ROOM by Antony Gormley
description: A monumental, inhabitable sculpture placed on a wing of the listed façade of The Beaumont Hotel. The interior, a bedroom, is as important as its exterior: a giant crouching cuboid figure based on the artist's body.
address: The Beaumont, Brown Hart Gardens, 8 Balderton Street, W1K 6TF

name: Rainbow Garden
description: A community garden in the very early stages, being developed in an abandoned land in Brampton Park using Community Assembly funds.

name: Reimagining the Great White City
description: Tour through White City regeneration projects, the scale of which not seen since 1908, when it hosted the Olympics and a Great Exhibition. See what remains at both sites taking in Television Centre, arising from the site’s ashes in 1960.

name: Richmond Lock Building (Surrey Side)
description:
A good example of quality late-Victorian functional design.
Richmond Lock &Weir consists of three 32 ton weir gates that operate 2 hours either side of high water.

name: Rio Cinema
description:
Grade II listed Art Deco cinema with stalls and circle created in 1937 within the shell of an Edwardian cinema, retaining many original features.
2017 new auditorium created in basement space.

name: Roca London Gallery
description: Designed by the world renowned Zaha Hadid Architects, Roca London Gallery is a unique space where water acts as the architectural theme. Guests can also visit 'Small Spaces in the City: Rethinking Inside the Box', a major exhibition exploring the challenges and innovative solutions for small live-and-work spaces in the city.

name: Romanian Cultural Institute
description: Situated in one of the largest and grandest 19th century squares in London, 1 Belgrave Square was acquired by Romania in 1936 and is now home to the Romanian Cultural Institute.

name: Royal College of Physicians
description:
Striking, provocative and one of London’s few Grade I listed post-war buildings. Drop in or take a tour of this award-winning building, from its modernist lines to dramatic interiors. 
See history.rcplondon.ac.uk/event/open-house-festival.
address: 11 St Andrew's Place, Regent's Park, NW1 4LE

name: Royal Opera House
description: Home to The Royal Opera, The Royal Ballet and the Orchestra of the Royal Opera House, the ROH was reconfigured in 2018 by Stanton Williams to offer world-class performance spaces and a welcoming and inclusive cultural and social hub.

name: Rudolf Steiner House
description: Unique example of Expressionist architecture in London with sculptural staircase based on organic plant forms. Grade II listed. New cafe area and renovations in 2008. Refurbishment of theatre and foyer 2020.

name: Russettings
description: A double-fronted red brick upper-middle class house, and one of a few Victorian villas to survive in Sutton. The well-preserved interior includes an entrance hall with a mosaic tiled floor, an oak galleried staircase and fireplaces.

name: Sandys Row Synagogue
description: Built as a Huguenot chapel in 1763, the building has been in continuous use as a synagogue since 1860 and retains many original features including the gallery. Oldest  remaining Ashkenazi synagogue in London and third oldest in the country.

name: Scadbury Moated Manor
description: See the archaeological excavations and Tudor foundations at Scadbury Moated Manor - which still has its moat around it.
address: Scadbury Moated Manor, Perry Street, Chislehurst, BR7 6LN

name: Seven Acre Lake, Canons Park Estate
description: Private 18C Seven Acre Lake, part of the dismantled Canons Mansion grounds, now surrounded by 1930s character housing. Wildlife includes Canada geese, swans and ducks.
address: Rose Garden Close, off Canons Drive, Edgware, HA8 7RF

name: Shrewsbury House
description: Built in 1923, to replace its 18C namesake, Grade ll listed Shrewsbury House is the focus of the Shrewsbury Park Estate conservation area, built 1934-1936 by John Laing and Sons. Two Civil Defence centres are within the grounds.

name: Sir John Soane's Museum
description:
The extraordinary home of architect Sir John Soane (1753-1837). 

https://www.soane.org/whats-on

name: St Anne's Church, Limehouse
description: St Anne's Limehouse has been described as 'the finest parish church in England.' Designed by Nicholas Hawksmoor, it is Grade I listed and one of the Major Churches in the Church of England. It is home to a thriving Christian congregation.

name: St John on Bethnal Green
description: This grade one listed Sir John Soane church sits in the heart of the Bethnal Green in East London. Despite a fire in 1870, some original features remain. Visitors will have access to the church,  belfry, galleries and crypt.
address: St John on Bethnal Green, 200 Cambridge Heath Road, E2 9PA

name: St Luke’s Catholic Church, Pinner
description: A suburban post-war Catholic church built in a neo-Romanesque version of the continental modern style by Velarde, next to the original neo-gothic church from 1915, now a parish centre, and alongside the modernistic 1960s parish hall.

name: St Martin's Parish Church, West Drayton
description:
A Grade II* listed church dating from 13th century with some interesting features
Adjacent to a 16th century Gate House

name: St Mary the Virgin
description: Small Grade I listed 12C chapel in lovely churchyard setting, it retains original architectural features and has interesting brasses, monuments and stained glass windows.
address: Church Road, Manor Park, Little Ilford, E12 6HA

name: St Mary's Church Bromley
description:
A plain Victorian Church set in a wooded Churchyard, with a vibrant and striking set of Murals around the altar and the Choir. 
Has indoor toilet facilities. 
A good quality well used organ in good condition, and an excellent accoustic
address: St Mary's Church, College Road, Bromley, BR1 3QG

name: St Mary's Church, Battersea
description: Classic Grade I listed Georgian church with outstanding interior and monuments. Renovated 2019/20.

name: St Nicholas Church
description: Built in the Gothic style with dressed flint and stone dressings. There are monuments to Joseph Glover (1628), Lady Dorothy Brownlow (1699), William Earl Talbot (1782) and Isaac Littlebury (1740). The churchyard has 5 Grade II tombs.

name: St Paul's, Newington
description: Modern architecture church with large copper and lead roof and concrete, brick and stained glass external structure. Marble, wood and plaster interior and artwork by Sculptor Freda Pinto and Gerald Holtom.

name: St Peter Church Petersham
address: Church Lane, off The Petersham Road, Richmond, TW10 7AB

name: Stationers' Hall
description: 17C livery hall with courtroom and garden. Oak panelling and stained glass windows. Undamaged in WWII. Recently refurbished new rooms and air-cooling within.  Selected items from the archives on display. Book binding exhibition in the Hall.

name: Stories from…The Welsh Chapel
description: An exhibition exploring the rapid technological changes in transport in the Sutton New Town Area (1870-1911). The Welsh Chapel is part of the Presbyterian Church of Wales - originally built as a Primitive Methodist Chapel in 1879.
address: Lind Road, Sutton, Greater London, SM1 4PJ

name: Surround Sounds
description: Surround Sounds: a listening, composing and performing workshop led by Rob Shuttleworth, an artist and musician. The workshop will take place in Stratford East London, using  local architectural sites as sonic material to respond to.

name: T J Boulting
description: Red brick and Portland stone corner building with three prominent signs in Arts & Craft style lettering in green and gold mosaic for the company 'TJ Boulting & Sons'.

name: Temple Bar
description: Temple Bar is a 350 year old gateway to the City of London, designed by Sir Christopher Wren. It formerly stood in Fleet Street, and was the last surviving gateway to the City of London.
address: First Floor, Paternoster Lodge, 2 Paternoster Square, EC4M 7DX

name: The American Other in London
description: Ever since the United States gained independence, Americans have been showing up again and again. This tour is about their influence on the UK from before the Revolutionary War to American heiresses marrying for titles to WWII to today.
address: Leicester Square Tube, Charing Cross Road, St Martin's Court

name: The Banqueting House
description: Stunning regal building, the only surviving building from Whitehall Palace, one of the first examples of the principles of Palladianism being applied to an English building. Site of a set of magnificent ceiling paintings by Rubens.

name: The Barbican & The City Gardens
description: Built on the site destroyed by The Blitz during the World War II, The Barbican Estate is a fascinating area and an icon of Brutalist architecture. Architects were Chamberlain, Powell and Bon,  We  will also visit several amazing gardens.

name: The British Academy
description: One of London's finest examples of Georgian architecture, Carlton House Terrace was designed by John Nash and built between 1827 and 1833. It is home to the British Academy, the UK’s national academy for the humanities and social sciences.

name: The Cartoon Museum
description: Underground museum. Interior design by Sam Jacobs Studio. Design concept influenced by cartoon and comic narrative techniques.
address: The Cartoon Museum, 63 Wells St, W1A 3AE

name: The Cumberland Hotel
description: Discover the breathtaking interior of London's iconic 1700s landmark, The Cumberland Hotel. Immerse yourself in its rich artistic history, once home to renowned artists. Join us to experience the allure of this extraordinary venue.
address: The Cumberland Hotel, Great Cumberland Place, W1H 7DL

name: The Electric Barge (Beauchamp), Grand Union Canal
description: The Electric Barge is a wide-beam canal boat moored in Paddington. The barge (with fully electric propulsion) was purpose designed and built for use as canal based classroom 20 years ago, operating as a charity: The Floating Classroom.
address: The Electric Barge (Beauchamp), Grand Union Canal, W2 6NA

name: The Gilbert & George Centre
description: The Gilbert & George Centre was originally established as a registered charity by the artist in 2009 with the objective to advance the education of the public in the arts, and generally to advance the arts, architecture, heritage and culture for the benefit of the public.

name: The Great Barn, Harmondsworth
description: The timbers of this great medieval barn (1426-7), over 190 feet long and nearly 40 feet high, are 95% original. Displays include the conservation/repairs carried out in 2014 and its place in the agricultural history of the village.
address: Manor Court, High Street, Harmondsworth, UB7 0AQ

name: The Great Fire of London
description:
In 1666, the conflagration devastated most of the City, thousands of houses, many churches and St Paul's Cathedral destroyed. Christopher Wren played a major role in rebuilding the City. 
Free walks led by City of London Guides

name: The Ismaili Centre
description: Part of an international family of Ismaili Centres, a religious, cultural and social space for the Shia Imami Ismaili Muslims. The serenity of the entrance fountain to the roof garden reflects Muslim traditions in architecture and design

name: The Marshall Building - London School of Economics and Political Science
description: A large multi-purpose building occupying a pivotal position at the southern corner of Lincoln’s Inn Fields.  The building provides state of the art, flexible teaching spaces on the lower levels and faculty accommodation on the upper levels.
address: The Marshall Building, 44 Lincoln's Inn Fields, WC2A 3PF

name: The Mysterious Black Tudors - Riverside Walking Tour
description: Celebrate the Open House Festival with this fun and interactive walking tour about Britain's forgotten history of the Black Tudors. Learn how African and European alliances, wars and conquests shaped the journeys of four Black Tudors.

name: The National Archives
description: South West London's hidden Brutalist masterpiece.
address: Ruskin Avenue, Kew, Richmond, Surrey, TW9 4DU

name: The Old Deanery
description: This Grade I Mansion House, close to St Paul's Cathedral was designed by Edward Woodroofe in 1669 and completed in 1673.  The residence of successive Deans of St Pauls until the 1970's today it is the office to the Bishop of London
address: The Old Deanery, Deans Court, EC4V 5AA

name: The Olde Forge Sanderstead
description: Sanderstead Smithy, now used by the Catholic Church and made into  the Olde Forge cafe. The building retains its original architecture and is of  historic interest being a former smithy built in the  early 1700s.

name: The Round House
description: Grade II* listed late Georgian elliptical 3-storey stuccoed villa.

name: The traces that remain: stories from Notting Hill
description: Not many would believe that Notting Hill, now an extremely wealthy part of London, was once notorious for being a “slum”. This tour explores the stories behind the streets of Notting Hill and how their effects can be seen decades on.
address: Outside Holland Park Station, Holland Park Avenue, W11 3RB

name: Timothy Hatton Architects – The Foundry
description: Tucked behind a busy road in W12, this former foundry is a multi-level development featuring an architects’ studio with courtyards and spaces for exhibitions and musical performances. The  building's 15m brick chimney is a local landmark.

name: Tower Hamlets Town Hall
description: Tower Hamlets Town Hall, the new headquarters for the London Borough of Tower Hamlets Council, encompasses the restoration of the Grade II listed former Royal London Hospital building, and the addition of a new build extension.

name: Trevithick House
description: Pre war social housing flats, red brick, Georgian sash windows, playground, allotments and washing lines outside.

name: Turning Earth Ceramics - In Production Open Studio
description: In Production is hosting its annual Open Studio on September 10th. A unique opportunity for the public to visit a professional pottery studio, the event will also include displays of our makers' ceramics, demonstrations, and food and drink.

name: Two Temple Place
description: Completed in 1895, Two Temple Place is a dazzling neo-Gothic gem on the Victoria Embankment, designed by gothic revivalist architect, John Loughborough Pearson, & commissioned by & built for William Waldorf Astor, as his estate office.

name: Tyrants, Colonialism and Slavery walking tour
description: A diverse walking tour, with a qualified guide, in the heart of Westminster where we visit some statues and places that have a significance to tyranny, colonialism and slavery.  The walk is accessible to all and ends in Trafalgar Square.

name: WWII fighter pen tours at former RAF Kenley
description: Join us for an open tour exploring the architecture, use, and restoration of the WWII fighter pens and air raid shelters that were part of RAF Kenley's airfield defenses.

name: Walking tour: Central Foundation Boys' School
description: Over the last 13 years, the 150-year-old school has reused and built upon its existing campus to provide new, state-of-the-art facilities. See how new architecture can sit with heritage buildings to create something completely new.
address: Central Foundation Boys School, Cowper St, EC2A 4SH

name: Waltham Forest Town Hall
description: Grade II listed Town Hall clad in Portland Stone. The building incorporates Art Deco and Nordic Classicism styles, also being influenced by the work of local activist William Morris. Extensively refurbished in 2019 by Hawkins Brown.
address: Waltham Forest Town Hall ,  Forest Road, E17 4JF

name: Walworth Garden
description: Our timber frame building was designed by Matrix Feminist Design Co-Operative, and built by women. It represents our community's history of activism-the same ethos that transformed our site from dereliction, into a thriving community garden

name: Waterloo City Farm
description: Feilden Fowles is situated within a walled garden on a discreet corner of Waterloo City Farm. Feilden Fowles designed the farm and its office and educational spaces, which is run by two charities: Jamie’s Farm and the Oasis Community Hub.

name: Wiener Holocaust Library
description: Sensitive yet bold refurbishment of historic Grade II listed townhouse for The Wiener Library including dramatic first floor reading room, mezzanine and ground floor exhibition spaces.

name: Wimbledon Windmill
description: Rare example of a hollow post mill (1817). Grade II* listed, it now contains a museum depicting the history and development of windmills in Britain. Many working models, windmill machinery, equipment and tools.
